<DOC><DOCNO> AP890520-0064 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-89 1216EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-20 0433</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0447</SECOND><HEAD>President Says He'll Name Commission to Talk Peace With Guerrillas</HEAD><BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Najib said Saturday he willappoint a commission to talk peace with Moslem guerrillas butwarned his troops are ready to ``inflict smashing rocket blows'' todefeat the rebels.   The guerrillas claimed to have killed at least 10 governmentsoldiers and shot down a Soviet-built jet in recent fighting.   Najib said the three-member commission would negotiate withrebels anywhere and at any time.   ``This is the best proposal we can make, and what more can I dofor an opposition that claims to hold 95 percent of the country?''Najib said in a speech to the opening session of the Loya Jirgah,which is empowered to decide matters affecting the country's future.   Members include the vice president, prime minister and hisdeputies, the Cabinet, and National Assembly members.   Najib said the commission would be selected by the Loya Jirgahand would talk to guerrilla commanders inside Afghanistan and torebel leaders in neighboring Pakistan and Iran.   The Loya Jirgah was called into session primarily to extend bythree months a nationwide state of emergency, which was declaredFeb. 18, three days after the last Soviet troops left Afghanistan.   The Red Army had been in Afghanistan for nine years to backNajib's troops in their war with the guerrillas, who are supportedby the United States and Pakistan and are based in Pakistan. Theyare fighting to topple the communist government and declare anIslamic republic.   ``The republic of Afghanistan, by making use of its legitimateand undeniable right for the defense of its independence andterritorial integrity, will infict smashing rocket blows on theAfghan armed extremists in Pakistan. There should be no doubts inthis regard,'' Najib said.   The president added that he would order a full mobilization todefeat the guerrillas, suggesting every male could be called formilitary service.   He also said he would draw on all available assistance fromMoscow, which continues to airlift food and weapons into Kabul.   In Pakistan, the guerrillas' Afghan News Agency said 10 Afghansoldiers were killed and at least 20 were wounded Thursday in arebel attack on the city of Jalalabad. The report made no mentionof guerrilla casualties.   Afghanistan's official Radio Kabul, monitored in Islamabad,claimed only one soldier died but that 153 rebels were killed.   The guerrilla news agency said rebels also attacked the militaryairport of the southeastern city of Kandahar on Thursday, wounding11 Afghan soldiers and shooting down a Soviet-built Mig-21 jetfighter.</TEXT></DOC>